19:45.395 --> 19:46.738
There's no peace level.

19:46.758 --> 19:49.142
It's what we call the inventory control part of it.

19:49.502 --> 20:00.240
And again, to use this as an example, not knowing anything about it, let's say this is a very important book and he wrote a preface in this edition, but which was not in this one.

20:00.861 --> 20:04.808
Or maybe he wrote something really important and showed up in this one that wasn't in this one.

20:05.210 --> 20:07.493
This database is not going to indicate any of that.

20:07.553 --> 20:12.678
It's just going to indicate it's just going to give you off the title, subject, you know, the place of publication.

20:12.698 --> 20:14.260
That's right.

20:16.423 --> 20:21.589
So basically, you know in the reading room that we have this title and this author.

20:21.609 --> 20:28.416
What you don't know is whether it's on the shelf, how many copies we have, or any of that type of information.

20:28.456 --> 20:31.280
An integrated library system is supposed to give us that information.

20:31.300 --> 20:33.462
A lot of public libraries and universal libraries have that.

20:34.167 --> 20:43.378
You can go and you can call up this title and it's going to say it's available in this branch and that branch and it's out in circulation or it should be on the shelf, all of that.

20:43.819 --> 20:57.595
So part of our concern when we started selecting materials that determining what was going to off-site storage had to do with the fact, how do we capture this information without an integrated system?

20:57.675 --> 21:00.939
And we're not going to have an integrated system for quite a few years.

21:01.179 --> 21:02.221
I mean, they're working on it.

21:02.241 --> 21:03.482
We're going to procure one.

21:04.357 --> 21:16.310
But if you're in the reading room, and just follow the scenario, because they're not great service for the scenario that we're really concerned with, and you, let's say we send this book off-site.

21:16.330 --> 21:20.074
Let's say it's only one copy of it.

21:20.335 --> 21:23.698
You're in the reading room, and you say, aha, I found how to read better.

21:24.159 --> 21:31.407
In the database, you go to the desk, you submit a call slip, you wait 45 minutes, you get a note on children.

21:31.427 --> 21:33.469
We have no way of knowing this book is off-site.

21:34.057 --> 21:35.960
You have no way to know this book is website.

21:35.980 --> 21:44.992
We have another system, our circulation system, which is an automated system, but it's not tied into our bibliographic database.

21:45.012 --> 21:48.177
So you come up to the desk and say, well, gee, I really need this book.

21:48.197 --> 21:49.379
I came from out of town.

21:50.560 --> 21:51.802
You could find it for me.

21:52.243 --> 21:55.888
We can go into our circulation file and say, aha, that book is in website storage.

21:56.268 --> 21:58.532
Would you like us to order it for you?

21:58.552 --> 22:03.118
But we would much rather people know that up front before they sit in the reading room and wait or all that.

22:03.503 --> 22:13.456
By sending entire class and subsets at this point, all of class S, if somebody orders a book in class S, as soon as they submit the call, we have a sign on the computer.

22:13.837 --> 22:22.529
If your book starts with an S, it's an off-site storage, please see a reference librarian or a technician, and we can tell you how we can get it for you from port meetings and all that.

22:22.549 --> 22:25.993
What do you think the turnover, the turnaround time for port meetings?

22:26.874 --> 22:32.582
We are operating on the premise that we're going to get a very responsive service, that we're going to have twice daily delivery, and

22:33.119 --> 22:37.985
It's one of the reasons we've avoided terms like remote storage, secondary storage.

22:38.005 --> 22:51.360
We're talking about off-site storage or high-density storage because we were really adamant that we wanted a facility that would be nearby, you know, within the ability to do a twice-daily round trip.

22:51.660 --> 22:52.401
And Fort Meade is.

22:52.461 --> 22:54.644
We can do a morning trip.

22:54.684 --> 22:55.765
Who owns the property?

22:55.785 --> 22:58.668
It's the Department of District of Defense.

22:58.688 --> 23:02.653
It's a military base, and it was a downsized military base, so they had some space.

23:03.038 --> 23:08.364
They transferred the property to the architecture.

23:08.384 --> 23:10.347
How much room do you have for modules?

23:10.647 --> 23:11.348
It's a lot of room.

23:11.568 --> 23:15.012
So, I mean, conceivably you can build 20 modules if you want.

23:15.032 --> 23:15.913
We can build 70.

23:15.973 --> 23:18.076
I mean, Harvard has space for 10, right?

23:18.096 --> 23:19.377
Yeah, we can build more.

23:19.938 --> 23:21.419
Well, that's good to know, isn't it?

23:22.000 --> 23:23.862
Over a long period of time.

23:23.882 --> 23:24.042
Right.

23:24.062 --> 23:26.245
Our current plan is to build a module over two years.

23:27.524 --> 23:34.834
So hopefully after the one that opens in 1999, if that's on schedule, there'll be another one in 21, 21, 23, 25.

23:35.314 --> 23:43.045
And when is the Fort Meade one opening?

23:43.065 --> 23:46.990
Supposedly summer of 99, the first module.

23:47.070 --> 23:50.655
At that point, 4,000 books a day.

23:50.675 --> 23:52.337
4,000 books a day.

23:52.638 --> 23:56.603
Five days a week, two and a half years to get a lot of this out.

23:56.836 --> 23:59.640
So what are you going to do for the next year and a half?

24:00.061 --> 24:00.662
After that?

24:01.062 --> 24:03.606
What are you going to do between now and the summer?

24:03.626 --> 24:09.254
Well, we're probably going to get in the next few years a half a million books that we have to make space for.

24:09.574 --> 24:09.795
Here?

24:10.095 --> 24:10.716
Here.

24:11.798 --> 24:14.862
And that's why they're on the floor, and that's why we're doing a lot of...

24:15.263 --> 24:19.589
Shifting, we're trying to double-shell, all kinds of creative things that we can do.

24:19.609 --> 24:29.041
When you press like this... It's a very great discomfort level for us, I can't believe, because we have sprinkler heads, and you don't want those sprinkler heads on the sprinkler heads.

24:29.061 --> 24:42.199
It's not a... You know, from a preservation point of view, a preservation office could tell you a whole bunch of things, but, you know, when you have books on the floor, that's a real problem as far as

24:42.938 --> 24:43.819
You know, being kicked.

24:43.919 --> 24:47.383
I mean, just the normal stuff, but water damage.

24:47.423 --> 24:54.751
When you have books that are very tightly packed on the shelf, people tend to pull them by the top and they're very tight and they rip through the top.

24:55.051 --> 24:57.273
They damage the book.

24:57.794 --> 25:03.980
There are areas you don't see even here where if you had a few taller books just to get an extra shelf, you've turned the book down.

25:04.020 --> 25:06.703
That damages the block.

25:06.723 --> 25:08.305
So there are a lot of preservation issues.

25:08.723 --> 25:13.648
One of the real upsides, I don't know if you've talked to me about Fort Meade and I'll say about our plan.

25:16.512 --> 25:26.202
We are designing, as far as we know, the state-of-the-art environmental system for that facility.

25:26.603 --> 25:33.671
We're building in everything to preserve the book, to preserve the physical item.

25:33.691 --> 25:37.515
The facility's going to be kept at 50 degrees Fahrenheit.

25:38.373 --> 25:41.236
which is much cooler than here, obviously.

25:41.256 --> 25:42.638
But it's excellent for paper.

25:42.658 --> 25:44.279
I think that's cooler than Harvard, too.

25:44.359 --> 25:45.821
Yes, it is cooler than Harvard.

25:45.841 --> 26:01.978
Thirty-five percent of all the humidity, special lighting, so it doesn't emit any harmful rays, sodium vapor lamps, very effective vapor barrier, air exchanges, dust-free environment, special floor covering.

26:02.079 --> 26:03.880
So it's just going to cost you a little figure on that?

26:03.900 --> 26:05.342
I don't have the exact figure on that.

26:05.744 --> 26:06.807
and what it's going to cost.

26:06.827 --> 26:18.403
And actually, the first module is going to be more expensive than the second, third, fourth, and fifth because we're building a lot of common loading dock and processing the work area staff area and all that.

26:18.721 --> 26:22.066
I mean, I can give you a figure, but I don't— Don't run the boat.

26:22.086 --> 26:22.927
I'm just curious.

26:23.027 --> 26:24.710
I'd say it's in the $4 million.

26:24.730 --> 26:26.232
It's not something like that.

26:26.332 --> 26:27.474
No, it's not.

26:27.494 --> 26:28.114
It's a warehouse.

26:28.135 --> 26:28.615
It's a shop.

26:28.896 --> 26:33.182
I mean, the real money is in making sure the environment is what we want.

26:33.322 --> 26:35.425
It's not a lot of money at all.

26:35.465 --> 26:40.092
No, and it's really going to be very, very close to—that's the construction course.

26:40.112 --> 26:42.375
I mean, that's the staffing and forklifts and all that.

26:42.395 --> 26:43.817
That's the National Library.

26:44.135 --> 26:48.919
And so, you know, the security out there is going to be much better, obviously.

26:49.000 --> 26:54.925
We're going to have high-level security, motion detectors, cameras, intrusion detection.

26:55.305 --> 26:58.008
Are you going to have any special collections out there?

26:58.028 --> 26:59.009
Any rare stuff?

26:59.089 --> 27:01.411
Not in the first module.

27:01.451 --> 27:07.177
There's discussion in the second module of having paper-based products that are not booked.

27:07.277 --> 27:10.800
And that would be things like maps, sheet music, and the scripts.

27:11.185 --> 27:16.295
That would obviously have a higher level, although the facility is going to be secure.

27:16.315 --> 27:21.125
I mean, are Harvidsons, the whole libraries and stuff that are departing here?

27:21.205 --> 27:25.294
Well, it's going to be secured, and it's on a military base.

27:26.416 --> 27:27.739
I don't think so.

27:27.959 --> 27:30.364
There won't be any public facilities out there.

27:30.384 --> 27:32.248
I mean, it's purely a work area.

27:33.022 --> 27:35.206
And I think Harvard is comparable to that.

27:35.466 --> 27:40.755
Yeah, Harvard is kind of, excuse me, Harvard, because the faculty were too free to send the books out there.

27:40.995 --> 27:41.977
They wanted a reading room.

27:42.037 --> 27:42.338
Right.

27:42.658 --> 27:45.022
So it's a coffee mess is what it amounts to, you know.

27:45.383 --> 27:47.206
But nobody ever goes out there to read.

27:47.226 --> 27:48.148
They don't allow it, you know.

27:48.248 --> 27:52.134
You know, we actually at one point talked about people going out there.

27:53.396 --> 27:54.338
And...

27:55.482 --> 27:56.623
Yeah, there are frozen kinds.

27:56.703 --> 28:00.227
If you have a scholar or a librarian, they want a whole bunch of stuff, isn't it better?

28:00.288 --> 28:03.411
If they're willing to go and try to transport, especially brittle material.

28:03.471 --> 28:05.554
You might have to have a curator there.

28:05.574 --> 28:09.298
You might have to have a copy machine.

28:09.979 --> 28:17.267
But the decision was taken away from us because I guess part of this transfer from the military, since it is on a military base, is no public facility.

28:17.688 --> 28:19.430
So that's part of the need of the transfer.

28:19.470 --> 28:20.711
So that decision was kind of made for us.

28:20.731 --> 28:21.452
It was made for us.

28:21.532 --> 28:22.333
It was taken out of our head.

28:22.600 --> 28:39.721
The one thing we are planning that Harvard does not have at this point, or at least didn't have the last time I went up there, was some level of content support services, because we are sending newer material.

28:39.821 --> 28:44.768
We are sending a lot of periodicals.

28:44.848 --> 28:45.789
Newer material, yeah.

28:46.149 --> 28:52.337
Yeah, because once we send, our premise now is once we send a class out, like Class S, like I have a poster,

28:52.621 --> 28:56.746
Any item that comes in here in agriculture and process is going directly out to Fort Meade.

28:57.607 --> 29:00.870
So it could be a 1997, at that point a 1999 item.

29:01.291 --> 29:02.712
That's generally not what Harvard does.

29:02.753 --> 29:03.914
But we also serve Congress.

29:03.934 --> 29:05.616
Ken was doing the same thing, though.

29:05.656 --> 29:09.360
He told me brand new stuff is going on.

29:09.380 --> 29:09.861
I said, really?

29:09.941 --> 29:10.722
Then why buy it?

29:10.962 --> 29:12.323
Because this is a private institution.

29:12.343 --> 29:13.525
This is not the Library of Congress.

29:14.165 --> 29:18.190
And he said, I was concerned I might have the same response from the administration.

29:18.524 --> 29:19.525
Because we didn't.

29:19.545 --> 29:20.346
Not a peep.

29:20.366 --> 29:24.031
Because there are certain things we know that we're buying it because we have to buy it.

29:24.131 --> 29:24.411
Right.

29:24.731 --> 29:27.475
And it may be necessary to have it.

29:28.215 --> 29:30.138
But there's no demand for it now.

29:30.238 --> 29:32.160
It goes straight out of the cell phone, you know?

29:32.380 --> 29:38.708
But we're not, unless it goes in a reference collection, even if you know there's demand, it's in one of those classes where a suspect is going after.

29:38.768 --> 29:43.013
So it's not an intellectual, this is probably something we should have, but.

29:43.887 --> 29:47.952
But I was saying, we also want to provide a very responsive reference service.

29:47.992 --> 29:53.418
We obviously have to provide highly responsive service to our top of the client, to Congress.

29:54.159 --> 30:04.090
So we are prepared to do photocopying of articles, look up something, faxing of things, which is something Harvard did not do.

30:04.110 --> 30:05.592
I mean, they deal with a physical piece.

30:06.263 --> 30:08.045
And we understand we've got a deal.

30:08.125 --> 30:14.513
If somebody needs an article for Congress, an author, a researcher, immediately on a rush request, we're willing to do that.

30:14.533 --> 30:20.160
That's going to have to involve the—you don't have to have a specialist out there, a librarian or a student.

30:20.180 --> 30:20.800
Well, maybe a technician.

30:20.820 --> 30:28.269
If they give us a citation of Sports Illustrated, you know, whatever it is, an article— Okay, but I mean, like the fellow whose name escapes me at the moment, Ron Lane.

30:28.670 --> 30:30.432
Ron Lane.

30:30.732 --> 30:38.703
I don't care if they send me the Gutenberg Bible, it's got a barcode on it, and it's in a box, because I don't know what the hell is in the box.

30:39.524 --> 30:41.587
We're not quite that extreme.

30:41.827 --> 30:43.589
Maybe he's being cute.

30:43.730 --> 30:44.931
No, he's not.

30:45.372 --> 30:47.615
He runs a superb facility.

30:48.055 --> 30:49.217
They never lose books.

30:49.898 --> 30:53.863
I mean, if he puts you through the whole process, they check, they double-check, they triple-check.

30:53.883 --> 30:55.025
I was totally impressed.

30:55.045 --> 30:57.448
It is a magnificent process, but...

30:58.306 --> 31:02.191
It is a total non-library setting, and Ron could be dealing with snakes.

31:02.291 --> 31:04.494
Ron's background is in the warehouse.

31:04.514 --> 31:08.059
Yeah, he could be dealing with shoeboxes, and that's fine.

31:08.079 --> 31:26.322
A lot of that's what we're going to do as a warehouse, but we really believe we cannot negate the other part of it, which is we do have to provide service, and we really are prepared, not professional reference service, but

31:26.622 --> 31:34.074
technician level reference, looking for articles, looking for, you know, being able to fax something in or that.

31:34.094 --> 31:36.298
And they've actually talked about that.

31:36.338 --> 31:40.725
If you ever watch a videotape at Harvard, they've actually talked about it.

31:40.745 --> 31:47.136
They don't do it, but they've talked in the past about maybe doing photocopying or faxing or, you know, if the libraries need that.

31:47.737 --> 31:50.101
Do they provide a videotape for people?

31:50.341 --> 31:50.521
What?

31:50.541 --> 31:51.583
There is a videotape.

31:52.171 --> 31:53.493
Harvard has a video tape?

31:53.513 --> 31:54.254
They have a video tape.

31:54.274 --> 31:57.339
It's kind of a promotional video tape.

31:57.359 --> 31:59.702
Well, I mean, do they invite?

31:59.722 --> 32:01.725
I don't know why we're selling it.

32:01.745 --> 32:03.368
I don't know why we're selling it.

32:03.388 --> 32:05.411
Yeah, because they're cost recovery.

32:05.451 --> 32:06.672
That's what I would think.

32:06.712 --> 32:09.256
They're probably selling their plans.

32:09.276 --> 32:12.661
They're selling, you know, they charge the service.

32:12.701 --> 32:13.863
Yep, tell me about it.

32:13.883 --> 32:18.530
Yeah, I mean, they charge storage and they charge the transaction.

32:18.630 --> 32:21.975
Yeah, they charge storage fee and they charge the transaction fee.

32:22.445 --> 32:24.527
To the actual units of the university.

32:24.808 --> 32:25.048
Yeah.

32:25.328 --> 32:26.389
He calls them customers.

32:26.990 --> 32:27.691
The customers.

32:28.011 --> 32:33.917
They charge for the new price, you know, how much material you have in each hole, each return.

32:34.037 --> 32:40.665
And in fact, if you are in the law school and you want a book today, it's going to charge you a hundred bucks.

32:41.405 --> 32:42.587
Otherwise, you'll get it tomorrow.

32:42.967 --> 32:43.708
Yeah.

32:43.888 --> 32:48.653
They charge you a hundred bucks from your account to my account to bring it in today.

32:48.713 --> 32:49.414
Yeah.

32:50.018 --> 32:53.083
And they have a whole free schedule for that.

32:53.143 --> 32:54.445
Obviously, we don't.

32:54.505 --> 32:55.607
That's not what we're doing.

32:56.088 --> 32:58.812
But we do have to provide service.

32:58.832 --> 33:04.681
Ron is very quick to point out, and I really believe this, that nobody likes immature field science.

33:04.701 --> 33:06.204
And we've gone through this.

33:06.324 --> 33:07.526
And we had the same.

33:08.367 --> 33:13.736
When we tried to select what was going out, it was always, well, something obviously has to go out.

33:13.756 --> 33:15.739
We have finite space that looks on the floor.

33:15.989 --> 33:17.752
You know, and I know you have to send something.

33:17.792 --> 33:20.135
Now let me tell you why my collection should not go.

33:20.255 --> 33:25.583
You know, it's always, you know, yeah, we have to cut the budget, but let me tell you why it shouldn't be my budget.

33:25.603 --> 33:28.687
Well, Ken's, Ron is not in that book.

33:28.747 --> 33:29.408
That's Ken's.

33:29.989 --> 33:30.510
Yeah.

33:30.530 --> 33:32.513
And they have, he's worked with the faculty.

33:32.533 --> 33:32.653
Right.

33:32.673 --> 33:34.015
They've set up the criteria.

33:34.135 --> 33:39.423
And the success Ron's had is that they have a superb operation.

33:39.563 --> 33:44.410
If they started losing books or not, you know, not be able to do next-day delivery...

33:45.065 --> 33:46.446
there would be problems.

33:46.466 --> 33:51.911
And we've told the people here, look, the book is not going to be here for browsing.

33:51.931 --> 33:55.034
But if you order in the afternoon, we're going to have it in the next day.

33:55.054 --> 33:59.859
If you order it in the morning or the end of the afternoon, and let me tell you the advantages of the facility.

33:59.879 --> 34:00.459
It's secure.

34:01.200 --> 34:03.923
It's got a state-of-the-art environmental control.

34:03.983 --> 34:13.772
And if you really care about the physical item, you want to protect it from deterioration or somebody just grabbing it or a sprinkler has it, the facility is going to be much better

34:14.258 --> 34:19.204
physical, environmental security protection than you would have here.

34:19.284 --> 34:21.607
And for a lot of people, that's very important.

34:21.627 --> 34:23.250
And once again, I'm under the gun.

34:23.290 --> 34:24.731
We have to produce.

34:24.892 --> 34:27.095
You can say we're going to do twice the end of delivery.

34:27.115 --> 34:27.815
We've got to do it.

34:28.637 --> 34:40.692
So, you know, it's... You're going to have another 500,000 new arrivals here by the time the Fort Meade departs are open.

34:41.413 --> 34:43.776
Is this kind of...

34:44.161 --> 34:50.286
encourage is not the correct word, but persuade you that maybe some books can do the accession.

34:51.888 --> 34:53.669
Well, why do you throw you loose in that?

34:53.689 --> 34:59.514
And I don't talk about it a lot, because I know Dr. Burns doesn't like the accession.

34:59.534 --> 34:59.935
But it happens.

34:59.955 --> 35:01.176
You know, we do some.

35:01.256 --> 35:04.839
I mean, there are things that go out of scope.

35:05.520 --> 35:08.983
You know, I mean, we have done an inventory of the collections.

35:09.123 --> 35:10.684
I don't know if you know anything about our inventory.

35:10.704 --> 35:12.666
Oh, I'd like to know about that.

35:13.186 --> 35:14.368
Yes, I would very much.

35:14.588 --> 35:20.176
The library never really did item-level inventory collections.

35:20.196 --> 35:23.501
And in the 1970s, there was a group of people.

35:23.521 --> 35:25.945
Do you want to sit over your case just a minute?

35:26.706 --> 35:27.367
Oh, fine.

35:27.387 --> 35:27.748
You're right.

35:27.768 --> 35:32.234
In the 1970s, the group of people got together to talk about the not-on-shelf rate.

35:32.355 --> 35:35.619
In fact, they had this not-on-shelf rate.

35:35.659 --> 35:38.063
NOS, not-on-shelf, is the term we used.

35:38.482 --> 35:44.467
When somebody asks for a book, requests a book, and it's not on the shelf, you get a response back that says, not on the shelf.

35:45.829 --> 35:49.012
And it could be not on the shelf for a variety of reasons.

35:49.032 --> 35:50.593
There was a lot of criticism back then.

35:50.633 --> 35:53.916
Well, the staff doesn't look for the book, you know, and all that.

35:54.517 --> 35:57.199
There are probably other reasons that it looks like not on the shelf.

35:57.219 --> 35:59.661
There are a lot of reasons for books not on the shelf.

35:59.681 --> 36:00.322
Some of them are good.

36:00.362 --> 36:01.183
Aretha's using them.

36:01.203 --> 36:02.264
I mean, it's in circulation.

36:02.304 --> 36:03.104
That's a positive.

36:03.184 --> 36:04.065
I mean, we're a library.

36:04.125 --> 36:05.026
We're not a warehouse.

36:05.707 --> 36:07.068
You know, our books are for use.

36:07.148 --> 36:08.269
So it's really good...

36:08.654 --> 36:11.777
when people are using our material.

36:12.738 --> 36:21.566
But, of course, if you're coming with a reading list, a group of people coming with a reading list, the first person gets a book, the other is getting an on-shelf report because the book is gone.

36:22.587 --> 36:36.720
But one of the things that was very clear is that we never did an inventory, in recent memory, we never did an inventory of collections, an item-by-item account, what we had, what might be somewhere else.

36:36.869 --> 36:39.393
And we figured there were a lot of reasons.

36:40.334 --> 36:42.978
Not only use, but something's a miscatalog.

36:43.679 --> 36:46.763
How could you possibly inventory 115 million items?

36:46.783 --> 36:51.510
Well, we started doing it in 1978, and we haven't finished it yet in 1997.

36:51.891 --> 36:53.553
So it's a long process.

36:53.633 --> 36:54.234
So where are you?

36:54.274 --> 36:56.978
And we're only dealing with a book collection.

36:56.998 --> 36:58.320
So 10 million.

36:58.340 --> 36:59.822
Roughly 10 million at this point.

37:00.342 --> 37:01.564
We've almost finished.

37:01.804 --> 37:02.965
We've almost finished.

37:03.025 --> 37:04.287
The first pass through.

37:04.307 --> 37:13.879
Yeah, but I'm going to say, by the time you're finished, you'll have another four or five million items that have to... So it's obviously going to be an ongoing... So what can you tell me about that?

37:13.919 --> 37:18.344
What we try to do is several things during this inventory.

37:18.364 --> 37:23.310
First of all, we try to account for every copy of every title.

37:23.591 --> 37:28.577
Now, there is this thing that I told you about, these 12 million card shufflers...

37:28.996 --> 37:36.345
It looks like a card catalog, but it's arranged the same way books are arranged on the shelf.

37:36.365 --> 37:40.931
They're in classified order, unlike an author title or a subject catalog.

37:41.051 --> 37:43.314
It's by calling.

37:43.334 --> 37:49.221
And not only does it have a card for each title you're supposed to have, but it also tells you how many copies.

37:49.862 --> 37:51.103
Copy one, copy two.

37:51.504 --> 37:58.092
It also tells you if the copy is somewhere else, like a rare book or something like that, if there's another assignment.

37:58.628 --> 38:10.732
So we literally had a staff that goes to the shelf with a shelfless tray and also the circulation file, because that was before the M1 made the circulation file, so they had a manual little thing of slips.

38:11.594 --> 38:17.927
And they'd go through and they'd say, gee, we had PN 83, I 84, 19, I copy 2, copy 1.

38:17.947 --> 38:18.628
Do we have it?

38:19.739 --> 38:21.701
They're doing this for all 10 million books.

38:21.721 --> 38:23.203
They did this for all 10 million books.

38:23.223 --> 38:23.883
How many people?

38:25.025 --> 38:27.487
Well, at one point, we were at our prime.

38:27.507 --> 38:29.870
We had about 30 people doing this.

38:30.310 --> 38:31.692
And now we have about 10 people doing this.

38:31.772 --> 38:32.192
Every day.

38:32.413 --> 38:34.975
Because we lost a lot of people.

38:35.056 --> 38:36.337
Yeah.

38:37.178 --> 38:43.505
And what they were trying to do, first of all, if a book was brittle or something, they were trying to put out preservation stuff.

38:43.525 --> 38:44.486
We had binding slips.

38:44.546 --> 38:45.206
We had preservation stuff.

38:45.226 --> 38:47.409
Did you have numbers on brittle books?

38:47.469 --> 38:47.569
Yeah.

38:47.988 --> 38:49.390
Not, no.

38:49.450 --> 38:49.751
Percentages?

38:50.452 --> 38:51.233
Do you have an idea?

38:52.395 --> 38:53.797
It depends on what's brittle.

38:53.997 --> 38:58.964
You know, we got this whole thing about fold tests, how many times you can turn the corner down before it breaks.

38:59.064 --> 39:00.266
What kind of a test?

39:00.286 --> 39:00.767
Fold.

39:00.907 --> 39:06.235
You know, something called a fold test, where you would actually, if you can, you know, turn it.

39:07.216 --> 39:13.626
The preservation has things where if you turn down a corner and it breaks after a certain period of time, then it's brittle.

39:13.766 --> 39:14.367
It's brittle.

39:15.055 --> 39:16.517
And I just noticed the folds there.

39:16.537 --> 39:17.759
And this one had a fold.

39:17.779 --> 39:19.181
I just actually opened to a fold.

39:19.242 --> 39:20.524
Yeah, I saw that.

39:20.544 --> 39:26.473
But if it breaks off after a certain period of time, it's a certain period.

39:26.493 --> 39:35.847
We have books that are just extremely adaptive cases, you know, literally.

39:35.868 --> 39:38.892
But did that make them candidates for deacidification?

39:38.952 --> 39:41.957
Well, probably more microfilming.

39:42.427 --> 39:48.276
You can't bind them, and deacertification, supposedly, is... I talked to those people yesterday, yeah.

39:48.296 --> 39:50.259
It's not a paper-strengthening process.

39:50.279 --> 39:52.081
It's supposed to slow down or stop.

39:52.141 --> 39:55.206
The paper's supposed to be working on something... Some strengthening.

39:55.226 --> 39:59.352
But this is... Our premise is we're not going to strengthen these things.

39:59.372 --> 40:01.816
But we did a lot of things in the inventory.

40:01.836 --> 40:02.697
Number one...

40:03.217 --> 40:09.224
we identified items needing binding, labeling, or probably microfilm.

40:09.625 --> 40:24.804
Number two, we replaced... Years and years ago, if you had soft-covered books or pamphlets that were not bound, that could not be bound, they were in something called a gay line.

40:25.204 --> 40:28.028
They were like these red folders.

40:29.369 --> 40:31.452
We replaced them all, but they were kind of

40:31.769 --> 40:39.099
like a red binder with a gray box, and then you would sew these things in or paste them in.

40:39.119 --> 40:48.771
And they were high in acidity, so they destroyed— Oh, okay.

40:49.212 --> 40:52.116
They destroyed the collection of hydrogen.

40:52.556 --> 40:57.363
And so we replaced these.

40:57.383 --> 40:59.345
These are all acid-friandes.

40:59.425 --> 41:01.388
I'm going to write down this title while you're talking.

41:01.722 --> 41:08.328
They're all acid-free, and so they won't destroy the book.

41:08.368 --> 41:15.515
Perhaps more importantly, we embarked upon a shelf marker project.

41:15.535 --> 41:28.807
And what a shelf marker is is a piece of cardboard with a facing stock on it that takes the place of the book on the shelf where it's supposed to be.

41:28.827 --> 41:29.828
I'm listening.

41:29.848 --> 41:30.328
So...

41:30.865 --> 41:44.604
This was very important to us because it told you if a book was not on the shelf, why it was not on the shelf.

41:46.446 --> 41:49.630
And I'm just looking for examples.

41:49.650 --> 41:54.477
For example, if a book is listening to you,

41:55.199 --> 42:08.402
Which means when we did this inventory, that specific time in history when we sat down here and we had the card looking for the book, the book was not on the shelf, we made up a shelf marker for the book.

42:09.143 --> 42:12.288
And this shelf marker took the place of the book.

42:12.308 --> 42:20.903
So if somebody wants Warren Schatz, Reading for Self-Education, his call number, this is specific copy three,

42:21.170 --> 42:24.574
We could tell them that this is missing an inventory.

42:24.594 --> 42:29.079
This book was noted as missing an inventory on November 24, 1982.

42:29.139 --> 42:31.062
This is a standard form.

42:31.262 --> 42:33.965
You got any around that I could have?

42:34.306 --> 42:35.287
I can get you.

42:35.307 --> 42:35.667
Do you mind?

42:36.008 --> 42:36.708
No, not at all.

42:37.289 --> 42:38.350
Can I give you my card?

42:38.631 --> 42:44.798
No.

42:47.343 --> 42:48.765
This was kind of interesting.

42:48.785 --> 42:50.528
I'll tell you two things about it.

42:50.548 --> 42:53.572
It's probably more about inventory than you want to know.

42:54.293 --> 43:00.762
This gave us what we consider a positive response to give to a reader who wanted this book.

43:00.782 --> 43:06.030
Because before we had shelf market, or somebody ordered this book, they would get back and not on shelf before.

43:06.050 --> 43:11.217
They would come up to the desk, they would say, gee, you know, what does this mean?

43:11.297 --> 43:13.420
I got this slip back, and it says, not on shelf.

43:14.041 --> 43:15.243
I said, that's what they said.

43:15.263 --> 43:16.725
I don't know.

43:17.077 --> 43:24.345
Maybe in circulation, somebody might be using it in the reading room, might be missing an inventory, might be missed shelves.

43:24.365 --> 43:25.126
That's not very helpful.

43:25.947 --> 43:28.610
You know, I mean, someone could put in a special search.

43:28.630 --> 43:37.100
But this way, if we could tell the person, this book, no, it's not on shelf, but it's missing an inventory, it's been missing an inventory, and we put the date on the call slip, 1983.

43:37.661 --> 43:43.708
At least we're telling the person, don't come back tomorrow, don't come back next Saturday, resubmit a call slip.

43:43.728 --> 43:45.750
And we do have people on the staff who will

43:46.203 --> 43:47.985
do a special search.

43:48.005 --> 43:50.688
We'll try to find another location that has the book.

43:50.708 --> 43:54.833
It might be Catholic University, American University, but we could actually try to find the book somewhere else.

43:54.893 --> 43:59.118
Now, I hope this is for somebody like in Congress, because this is not for the general reader.

43:59.138 --> 44:00.239
This is for the general public.

44:00.259 --> 44:04.964
I mean, we will try— We would hope that the general public would go to the other facility and— Well, yes.

44:05.144 --> 44:11.772
But if they're here and they say, well, gee, I really need this book, we can look at national catalogs and other things and try to find another library.

44:12.157 --> 44:21.708
So even though they're not getting a book with something like this, we do consider a much more positive response, like we know what we're doing, other than just not on shelf to say it's missing in inventory.

44:21.728 --> 44:23.030
We know that.

44:23.110 --> 44:26.574
Can we help you find another spot to get the book?

44:26.654 --> 44:29.518
Now, did we finish the question on deaccession?

44:29.538 --> 44:32.982
You said, I know Dr. Bollinger doesn't like to discuss that.

44:33.082 --> 44:34.363
We're a national library.

44:34.443 --> 44:35.685
We don't do a lot.

44:35.725 --> 44:36.886
We do do some.

44:37.006 --> 44:39.089
I started saying with the inventory.

44:39.449 --> 44:40.851
There were criteria.

44:40.891 --> 44:41.792
There were certain criteria.

44:42.143 --> 44:49.372
categories of material that are out of scope that we might have collected at one point that are now considered out of scope.

44:49.392 --> 44:50.893
Can you give me an example?

44:51.454 --> 44:51.815
Yeah.

44:52.215 --> 44:57.141
And every time, I can say, every time, when we did the inventory, we did it class by class.

44:57.181 --> 45:01.746
So we did class E, and then we did class B, and then class P, and all that.

45:02.968 --> 45:07.233
We went to the collections policy, collections development people, and we were recommending them.

45:07.253 --> 45:08.735
So we said, okay, we're going to do this.

45:09.736 --> 45:11.458
Can you recommend, you know, give a,

45:11.675 --> 45:16.401
They gave us criteria for what we should be looking at weeding out.

45:16.781 --> 45:20.106
Now, in certain cases, it was multiple copies.

45:20.466 --> 45:31.139
We might have collected a large number of copies, and at one point, we decided in certain classes we only keep one copy of a foreign language and two copies of English language material.

45:31.159 --> 45:36.366
So if we had foreign language copies two and three, or we had English language copies two and three,

45:36.987 --> 45:39.870
we might have discarded them, weeded those out.

45:39.890 --> 45:40.851
Of the same edition?

45:41.171 --> 45:42.672
Yeah, the same edition.

45:42.692 --> 45:43.153
Is it good?

45:43.753 --> 45:45.215
Multiple editions?

45:45.235 --> 45:47.036
No, we keep them.

45:47.056 --> 45:49.498
And I think there's an example of this, how to read fast and better.

45:49.518 --> 45:52.361
This is two copies of one edition, two of the other.

45:52.701 --> 45:58.967
Even if I said copies two and three, if we couldn't find a copy of one, we would keep two copies, so we would keep copies of three.

45:58.987 --> 46:04.412
So we would weed out copies above a certain number.

46:04.763 --> 46:08.027
For example, we went to class L, which is education.

46:08.567 --> 46:13.012
They told us to generally weed out high school yearbooks.

46:13.693 --> 46:15.094
We weren't keeping high school yearbooks.

46:15.114 --> 46:19.799
At one point, I guess, years ago, we collected some high school yearbooks.

46:19.819 --> 46:21.901
So what happened to them?

46:21.962 --> 46:26.787
They're generally sent to exchange and gift.

46:26.807 --> 46:32.593
More recently, we've had projects in medicine where we've gone through and started

46:32.843 --> 46:35.826
reducing some of the copies.

46:36.166 --> 46:45.015
Yes, and in that case, we actually offered these to the National Library of Medicine, and then the things they didn't warrant, we sent down this change in gift.

46:45.035 --> 46:48.258
But we had a cooperative project with the National Library of Medicine.

46:48.358 --> 46:49.899
And agriculture would do this.

46:49.919 --> 46:52.061
Agriculture, we don't collect that comprehensively.

46:52.081 --> 46:57.467
I mean, we don't collect that comprehensively, clinical medicine affecting the agriculture to begin with.

46:58.287 --> 47:02.091
So there are sometimes additional copies of something like high school yearbooks,

47:02.628 --> 47:04.290
textbooks all in a certain date.

47:04.350 --> 47:15.566
There were certain things that we would not retain, you know, and as part of the inventory, we actually did some weeding, you know, according to those criteria.

47:15.886 --> 47:22.034
Now, in all those cases, we, you know, this is a staff of technicians doing this, according to very specific guidelines.

47:22.054 --> 47:23.256
So nothing ever went out.

47:23.376 --> 47:32.128
We kind of gathered them, and we had the specialist to recommend an officer review them, because if they said, gee, this is a really important work, and even though

47:32.362 --> 47:34.145
We really want to keep more copies.

47:34.165 --> 47:38.351
Did you keep a record of the books that you were able to get rid of?

47:38.371 --> 47:41.797
Not, well... I just got back from San Francisco.

47:41.857 --> 47:56.439
The answer is yes in the fact that the shelf list, which is that card file, which is still in existence, is the only way that we would mark, for example, next to copy three, discard.

47:56.579 --> 47:59.043
So what you're telling me is you kept a record.

47:59.063 --> 48:00.225
Oh, yeah, it's in the shelf list.

48:00.357 --> 48:01.859
San Francisco didn't keep a record.

48:01.879 --> 48:02.059
Oh, no.

48:02.079 --> 48:03.922
200,000 books went to the landfill.

48:04.002 --> 48:05.103
Nobody can tell you what they are.

48:05.123 --> 48:05.444
No, I know.

48:05.484 --> 48:10.971
That's... No, this is... Because we have the inventory... The shelf list is the inventory record.

48:11.612 --> 48:15.878
And so we... They mark the shelf list for that copy.

48:16.138 --> 48:17.701
We have shelf list.

48:17.941 --> 48:19.603
Steve, before I forget, what's your phone number?

48:19.623 --> 48:23.809
202-707-1410.

48:24.650 --> 48:26.232
I have to sign books in an hour.

48:26.252 --> 48:26.533
Okay.

48:26.553 --> 48:29.757
I have to go to my hotel and check out... Okay.

48:30.007 --> 48:32.752
These are other, for example, this book is in rare book.

48:32.992 --> 48:34.475
Once again, shelf markers.

48:35.196 --> 48:38.021
Years ago, somebody asked for this book, the N85.

48:38.722 --> 48:39.423
It's not on the shelf.

48:39.443 --> 48:40.846
They were going to not on shelf before.

48:40.866 --> 48:41.647
And that would be it.

48:42.048 --> 48:42.889
That's all they get.

48:42.910 --> 48:46.235
And now they come up to that and say, where it is, we'll do a special search.

48:46.716 --> 48:47.938
But this book is a rare book.

48:47.958 --> 48:48.820
It's not even missing.

48:48.860 --> 48:52.386
I mean, it's one floor away, and it's accessible to the person.

48:52.636 --> 48:55.720
So now if somebody asks for the book, we say, that is in the rare book collection.

48:55.740 --> 49:00.686
What do you call the people that come in here and do that check, the shelvers or the pages?

49:00.706 --> 49:02.388
These were collections improvement systems.

49:02.408 --> 49:08.696
The people that actually, oh, the people that page or the people that... No, the person that comes down and can't find that book.

49:11.920 --> 49:19.369
But this is really important because we have a lot of stuff on microfilm, and we have a lot of things in the rare book or in the reference collection.

49:19.568 --> 49:22.192
And, you know, people have just gotten it on the shelf before.

49:22.212 --> 49:23.914
Now they actually can get right to the book.

49:23.934 --> 49:24.615
We tell them where it is.

49:24.635 --> 49:29.461
And the item-by-item inventory that you've done, is that all in computer now?

49:29.501 --> 49:30.743
Because it started in the 70s.

49:31.244 --> 49:32.585
Do you have a database now for that?

49:32.605 --> 49:33.166
There is not a database.

49:33.186 --> 49:33.927
Any kind of retrospective stuff?

49:33.947 --> 49:34.648
There is not a database.

49:34.688 --> 49:36.050
It's all in manual form.

49:36.070 --> 49:36.631
And it should be.

49:36.711 --> 49:41.798
And when we get the integrated library system, one of the promises, we can enter all this into the database.

49:42.158 --> 49:45.362
So it's all online, so I know something's missing in inventory.

49:45.563 --> 49:46.504
That's long-range.

49:46.940 --> 49:55.415
Yeah, the system is probably shorter range, but the system is going to do a lot of things, and before you input 12 million cards and all of this, it's going to be quite a while.

49:55.436 --> 49:56.417
So we can start walking.

49:56.558 --> 49:57.299
Okay.

49:57.359 --> 49:59.122
How are you?

49:59.383 --> 50:02.048
And how long have you been here?

50:03.069 --> 50:04.392
In this job, 20 years.

50:04.712 --> 50:07.237
And your background, just briefly, you said you're a librarian.

50:07.297 --> 50:07.978
Librarian.

50:07.998 --> 50:08.880
I was a public...

50:09.383 --> 50:11.166
We worked for a small public library.

50:11.566 --> 50:11.927
Where?

50:12.407 --> 50:13.689
In New Jersey.

50:13.729 --> 50:18.516
So you don't sound like you came from Kentucky.

50:18.676 --> 50:19.898
I came from New Orleans.

50:20.539 --> 50:23.163
I was working with a blind handicapped in New Jersey.

50:23.223 --> 50:29.752
That sounds like an interesting... We were in the library for the blind handicapped in New Jersey.

50:30.533 --> 50:38.665
Is that a major... Well, part of the Library of Congress is called the National Library of Science for the Blind and Physically Handicapped.

50:38.881 --> 50:42.304
